7. Marginal structural model

2023-06-27

Back to content page

Learning objective

  • Recognize the situation in longitudinal study with time-dependent confounder
  • Analyse longitudinal data using Marginal Structural Models (MSM), accounting for endogenous confounding
  • Recognize the assumptions of MSM
  • Interpret the results from MSM

1 Endogenous confounding

Endogenous confounding

Endogenous confounding = time-dependent confounders

  • Difficult to establish causality in observational study
  • Figure: If there is time element, confounder L is also mediators, e.g. A1 -> L2 -> Y. But we cannot adjust for mediator. Example:
    • Obesity (A), CVD (L), all-cause mortality (Y)
      Obesity => CVD
      CVD unlikely to do exercise => Obesity
    • Influenza vaccine (A), health status (L), influenza virus infection (Y)
    • Depressive symptoms (A), health behavior (L), stroke (Y)

MSM using IPW

Strategy to control for endogenous confounding – MSM

  • Imagine we can ‘clone’ the subject with identical characteristics, except taking opposite treatment (counterfactuals) => can estimate causal effect by Y1 - Y0
    • We can regard counterfactuals as missing data (unobservable in reality, each subject either take or not take drug)
    • Then use IPW to reweight the dataset to balance the predictor/confounder on two groups (like in RCT)
      • At each time point, the probability was estimated conditional on past confounders and may also on past responses (depending on the assumed causal structure)
      • Treatment can also be time-dependent
      • Can also handle dropouts similarly
      • Called propensity score for time-independent case
  • Marginal Structural Model (MSM) = the model that use IPW mentioned above
    • “Marginal” = do not model the correlation between observed outcome and counterfactuals (we don’t care abt it)
    • “Structural” = model the probabilities of counterfactuals varaibls (terminology from econometrics or social science)
    • Use Inverse probability of treatment weighed (IPTW) estimator
      • => Can then be applied to GLM, Cox regression or GEE
        MSM just a way to handle time-dependent confounding, we still need to specify relationship between outcome Y and covariant X like linear or logistic regression

Assumptions of MSM

  1. No unmeasured confounders
    • However not testable
    • Need to search literature to possible common confounders, or do sensitivity analysis
  2. Experimental treatment assignment / Structural positivity
    • Cannot have complete confounding (probability = 0 or 1)
      • complete confounding = confounding variable perfectly predict exposure (they perfectly correlates, correlation between them is 1 or -1) so we cannot separate effect from confounding and exposure.
      • weighting should be away from 0 or 1
  3. Models are specified correctly, e.g. linear or logistic regression

Steps for MSM

Recap on IPW

  • Have some weight (probability of treatment) to balance the conditioning
    • Unstable weight is problematic – Extremely large weighting may dominate the further weighted analysis and increase the variability
    • Hence stablilized weight is proposed – P(A) appearing in both numerator and denominator helps to reduce the variation of the weights
      Unlikely to get extreme value , e.g. when unstable weight is 200, stable weight is 100
      • Always use stablized weight for continuous exposure variable
      • Stabilized weight for diff time point: can multiply weight tgt if > 1 time point

Standard error for MSM

  • Robust standard error estimator is needed to account for correlation (e.g.  sandwich estimator) because
    • correlation is induced by weighting
    • longitudinal data also hv within-subject correlations
  • Bootstrap method to obtain the standard error can also be used.

2 MSM without time(R)

R code

  • R package: ipw.
  • ipwpoint, ipwtm to generate inverse probability weighting for situations with time-independent and time-varying exposure/confounder
    • ipwpoint(exposure, family, link, numerator = NULL, denominator, data, )
      • exposure…the exposure/treatment variable of interest
      • family…the famiily of the relation, e.g. “binomial”, “multinomial”, “ordinal”, “gaussian”
      • link…the link function, e.g. “logit” for logistic regression, “gaussian” for linear regression, other links are also possible
      • numerator…the predictors in the numerator of IPW. If unspecified, unstabilized weights = 1 will be used
      • denominator … the predictors in the denominator of IPW. Confounders should be included.

1 Example – generate dataset

First, generate simulated data from van der Wal et.al 2011 (A)

  1. \(L \sim N(10, 5^2)\)
  2. \(logit(P(A=1)) = -10 + L\)
  3. \(Y = 10A + 0.5L - 10 + \epsilon, \text{where }\epsilon \sim N(0, 5^2)\)

So we know that the true causal effect of A on Y is 10 (Y = 10A + …)

  • This can be estimated by standard linear regression by adjusting for L
  • An alternative is to use IPTW estimator => learn this in this lecture
  1. Estimate the weights (B)
  2. Obtaining IPTW estimates with package survey (C)
    • use svyglm() to fit the MSM model applying IPW
      • svydesign(id, weights, data) to specify the weighting (id ~ 1 for no clusters)
      • svyglm will give the robust estimator for the standard error, accounting for the clustering effect introduced by weighting
    • The IPW will balance the confounder (L) and hence is not adjusted for in the model (l already handled by weighting, so y~a instead of y~a+l)
### A Generate dataset
set.seed(111)
## 1 Simulate 1000 observations (L) following normal distribution
n <- 1000
simdat <- data.frame(l = rnorm(n, 10, 5)) 
## 2 Generate A based on L
a.link <- simdat$l - 10 
pa <- exp(a.link)/(1 + exp(a.link)) #Probability of having treatment in each individual
simdat$a <- rbinom(n, 1, prob = pa) #Generate 1000 treatment status based on probability obtained
## 3 Generate Y based on A and L
simdat$y <- 10*simdat$a + 0.5*simdat$l - 10 + rnorm(n, 0, 5)
simdat[1:4,] #Preview of simulated dataset
##           l a           y
## 1 11.176104 1  12.9941002
## 2  8.346321 0  -0.5416105
## 3  8.441881 0 -11.8720489
## 4 -1.511728 0  -9.6681398

2 Weight and estimate

Stabalized weight

### B Estimate the stabalized weights (sw)
library(ipw)
temp <- ipwpoint(exposure = a, family = "binomial", link = "logit", numerator = ~ 1, denominator = ~ l, data = simdat) #a is binomial; link is logit; numerator 1 coz probability is like constant; denomiator l coz confounding variable is considered
summary(temp$ipw.weights) #despite it's stabalized, the max can go up to 100 (unstabalized more extreme)
## ipwplot() to show the distribution of the weights
ipwplot(weights = temp$ipw.weights,logscale = FALSE,main = "Stabilized weights", xlim = c(0, 8)) #plot weight out

summary(temp$num.mod) #numerator model
summary(temp$den.mod) #denominator model, estimate of l is ~1 and intercept is 10 => close to our real model

### C Obtain IPTW estimate
simdat$sw <- temp$ipw.weights #save the weight
require(survey)
msm <- svyglm(y ~ a, design = svydesign(~ 1, weights = ~ sw, data = simdat)) #id 1 for no clustering in dataset

confint(msm)[2,] #95%CI
#The estimate causal effect of A on Y is 10.9 (95% CI = 9.2 12.5)

3 MSM with time (R)

R code

  • ipwtm(exposure, family, link, numerator = NULL, denominator, id, tstart, timevar, type, data, )
    • exposure, family, link, numerator, denominator, data same as ipwpoint
    • id…identifies the cluster/subject where multiple measurements were made (indicate which observation come from the subject)
    • tstart…the start time of the follow-up intervals, only needed when family = “survival” (tstart should be < 0 for the first interval
      => usually start from time 0 in actual dataset => subtract that by 100 or 1 to make sure it’s <1 and model know its first time point
    • timevar… follow-up time. When family = “survival”, it specifies the end time of the follow-up intervals
    • type…the type of exposure. Type = “first” estimates weights up to the first switch of the exposure value (e.g., for death, from 0 to 1) then keep constant afterwards. Alternative is type = “all” that weights were estimated at all time points.

Example

  • Dataset from ipw package, can be loaded by data(haartdat)
    • 1200 HIV patients was followed every 100 days since HIV seroconversion
    • HAART therapy are initiated which may depend on CD4 counts
      • tstart, fuptime: start and end of the follow-up interval
      • haartind: indicate whether HAART therapy was initiated in the follow-up interval (treatment)
      • event: indicator of death at the end of the interval
      • age: age at the start of follow-up year
      • cd4.sqrt: square root of the CD4 counts

2a Weight for endogenous confounding

2a. Estimate the weights (Handle time-dependent confounding CD4 count)

### 2a Estimate the weights (Handle time-dependent confounding CD4 count)
## stabalized weight (numerator = time-independent confounding; denominator = time-dependent confounding)
temp <- ipwtm(exposure = haartind, family = "survival", 
              numerator = ~ sex + age, denominator = ~ cd4.sqrt + sex + age,
              id = patient, tstart = tstart, timevar = fuptime, type = "first", data = haartdat)
## unstabalized weight (remove numerator element)
temp.uns <- ipwtm(exposure = haartind, family = "survival",
                  denominator = ~ cd4.sqrt + sex + age, id = patient, tstart = tstart,
                  timevar = fuptime, type = "first", data = haartdat) 
## Comparison: distribution of Log stabalized and unstabalized weight in diff time point can be displayed by ipwplot()
ipwplot(weights = temp$ipw.weights, timevar = haartdat$fuptime,
        binwidth = 100, ylim = c(-1.5, 1.5), main = "Stabilized weights",
        xaxt = "n", yaxt = "n")

3 Estimate

Fitting MSM

  • Robust (sandwich) standard error was used to account for the correlation among patient
    • Provided when using coxph with cluster() to specify correlated observations
## Estimate from stabalized weight
require(survival)
summary(coxph(Surv(tstart, fuptime, event) ~ haartind + cluster(patient), data = haartdat,
              weights = temp$ipw.weights*temp2$ipw.weights)) #multiply weights tgt; don't include age, sex, cd4 count coz alr handled by weighting

4 Review

Model diagnositcs

  • Assumption 1: Unconfoundedness between treatment and predictors
    • Not testable
    1. More likely by identifying and including relevant confounders from the literature (diligently)
    2. Perform sensitivity analysis by including other potential confounders
  • Assumption 2: Experimental treatment assignment / structural positivity
    • Plot the distribution of the stabilized weight, see whether extreme values indicate potential violation of positivity (see if extreme value is too big)
    • Mean value far away from 1 indicates model mis-specification
    • However, this is just simple guideline, cannot make too much indication…

Review

  • Marginal structural model estimates the causal effects of treatment/exposure for longitudinal data, accounting for endogenous confounders
  • Inverse probability of treatment weighed (IPTW) estimator is used to
  • Robust standard error are used to account for correlation induced by IPW and/or within-subject correlation

Note: 1. use stabalized weight by indicating the “numerator” 2. do not include confounders in regression model, otherwise will doubly adjusted for them

Real-life example

  • Estimating the Time-Varying Joint Effects of Obesity and Smoking on All-Casue Mortality Uisng Marginal Structural Models by Banack et al. AJE, 2016
    • Objective: to estimate the joint effects of obesity and smoking on all-cause mortality
    • Study design: prospective longitudinal study
    • Subjects: 15,792 men and women aged 45 64 years old in the US
      • CVD is an endogenous confounder
      • Steps: First calculate the weight. Then fit a poisson regression.
      • Result: MSM estimated a relatively higher effect of obesity than from adj. model
